<font color="#FF0000">A FEW COMMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar 11  2:35:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am very pleased to see that this site is alive and well. I was the second post to this site in December, 1996, in answer to questions by Professor Grivetti.<br><br>
Since that time, I have been occupied with significant educational experiences on Vietnam, my feelings about my involvement, what I still carry with me, and the views of others. It continues to be an extraordinary journey.<br><br>
Please do not falter in your goals of a better education on Vietnam. It will not only help students of today and of the future, but it is invaluable for those of us who were there and continue to sort things out in our lives. It is a very creepy feeling when I recall that I actually lived some of this history, and despite some personal cynical feelings at times, it gratifies me to see it continuing very much alive and vital.<br><br>
Recently, I said somewhere else:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;The Vietnam War history, like so many other histories, will inevitably become featureless and stale theoretical renditions in time, destined to<br>
bore thousands of students to death in those dreaded seventh period Friday afternoon classes just before spring break.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
I challenge everyone to prove me wrong! Please!   
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


